default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK will not meet its low carbon targets with current technologies at today’s costs.  Innovation in low carbon technologies is essential if we are to transition to a low carbon society cost effectively.  
defaultGiven its scale, complexity and interdependencies
default, the energy system can neither be transformed quickly nor by a single “silver bullet”. Rather, innovation must occur across a broad front 
defaultfrom generation through to use, at a component and system level.
default  
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLow carbon technologies can take decades to develo
defaultp, with inherently high costs and risks during pre-commercial stages. 
defaultMarket failures and barriers include p
defaultoor market signals, long payback periods, under-developed supply chains
default,
default and knowledge spill-overs that make it cheaper to replicate existing techno
defaultlogies than to develop 
defaultthem
default from scratch. 
defaultThese
default barriers have meant that businesses have tended to under-invest in low carbon innovation
default.  
default At the same time, while market incentives provide confidence to technology developers that there will be a return on
default investment, in many cases these are not 
defaultsufficient t
defaulto drive the required innovation.  Low carbon innovation is normally taken forwards by different businesses with different skills sets to those deploying the technologies which receive incentives.
default 
defaultFor exa
defaultmple, bioenergy technologies requires considerable up-front investment across the entire agricultural supply and value chain to realise future benefits as well as investor confidence and a 
defaultsupportive policy environment.  To fully realise the benefits will 
defaultrequire a thirty year time horizon, but 
defaultonce established the returns from well managed energy crops are effectively sustainable indefinitely.
default8.
